HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1108
By Clemmons
A RESOLUTION to honor Hillsboro High School, winner of the
MNPS High School Battle of the Books.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly recognize those
industrious, talented students of Tennessee who bring pride and honor to our State; and
WHEREAS, the students of Hillsboro High School recently proved victorious during the
Metro Nashville Public School's (MNPS) High School Battle of the Books, besting thirteen other
district schools in a show of teamwork and dedication; and
WHEREAS, the MNPS High School Battle of the Books is an annual, book-centered
trivia competition sponsored by the Library Services Department; begun in 2012, the
competition promotes literacy, teamwork, and deeper engagement with school library resources;
and
WHEREAS, a committee of school and public librarians select twelve books for the
competition each year; the books must be high-quality, recently published works that represent
a variety of fiction and nonfiction genres; and
WHEREAS, one of the books selected is by a local author, who is invited to speak to
students at the event, and students receive a signed copy of the book, courtesy of the
Parnassus Foundation; and
WHEREAS, the event is planned by Dr. Alyssa Littrell from MNPS Library Services with
the support of numerous volunteers from MNPS and the Nashville Public Library; participation in
the Battle of the Books is an extracurricular activity that challenges students to read beyond
their assigned classroom texts; and
WHEREAS, high school librarians promote the opportunity to all students and select and
coach a team; each team consists of five students who read a shared list of twelve young adult
HJR1108
015629
- 1 -

fiction and nonfiction titles, log many hours of practice, and compete against other schools in the
district; and
WHEREAS, the competition includes three preliminary rounds, after which the four
highest scoring teams advance to the semifinal round; the top two teams then move on to the
final round, where one team is awarded the first-place title; and
WHEREAS, in each round, teams answer twenty questions centered on trivia from the
twelve titles on the Battle of the Books reading list; and
WHEREAS, this year's High School Battle of the Books was held on February 18, 2026,
at the Martin Professional Development Center in Nashville; fourteen high school teams
participated in the highly competitive event, and after answering one hundred questions about
the twelve titles, Hillsboro High School took home the first-place trophy; and
WHEREAS, in addition to Hillsboro High School, the participating schools and their
librarian coaches were Antioch High School, Lauren Williams; East Nashville High School, Tyler
Sainato; Glencliff High School, Julie Halkiades; Hume-Fogg High School, Amanda Smithfield;
Hunters Lane High School, Amy Carlson; James Lawson High School, Natalia Fallon; John
Overton High School, Krista Winningham; Maplewood High School, Karen Yarbrough; Martin
Luther King Jr. School, Cami Townsel; McGavock High School, Kim Norment; Nashville School
of the Arts, Hope Hall; Stratford High School, Diane Chen; and Whites Creek High School,
Kearea Brady; and
WHEREAS, the students at Hillsboro High School were coached by school librarian
Joyce Claassen, whose wisdom and encouragement proved vital to the team's success; and
WHEREAS, the display of aptitude and ambition by the students at Hillsboro High
School surely bodes well for their future success, and their dedication to excellence is clearly
deserving of our respect, admiration, and commendation; now, therefore,
- 2 - 015629

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we commend and congratulate Hillsboro High School, winner of the MNPS
High School Battle of the Books, extending our best wishes for much continued success.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
